Why This Is Asked
- Tests ability to design streaming, multi-format log processing with compression and nesting.
- Probes time-window handling, per-tenant aggregation, and memory-conscious streaming.
- Evaluates how to gracefully skip unreadable files without failing the pipeline.

Key Concepts
- POSIX shell pipelines and standard tools (tail, zcat, awk)
- Mixed log formats (text and JSON) parsing without external parsers
- Sliding window aggregation per tenant/service
- Deduplication by message content within a time bucket

Code Example
```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
# Skeleton illustration
tail -F /logs/tenant-*/service-*/{*.log,*.log.gz} 2>/dev/null | \
zcat -f 2>/dev/null | \
awk '
function parse_ts(line) {
    if (match(line, /^[0-9]{4}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{2} [0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2}/)) {
        return substr(line, RSTART, 19)
    } else if (match(line, /"ts":[0-9]+/)) {
        return strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S", substr(line, RSTART+5, RLENGTH-5))
    }
    return ""
}
function parse_level(line) {
    if (match(line, /^[0-9]{4}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{2} [0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2} ([A-Z]+)/)) {
        return substr(line, RSTART, RLENGTH)
    } else if (match(line, /"lvl":"[A-Z]+"/)) {
        gsub(/"lvl":"/, "", line)
        gsub(/".*/, "", line)
        return line
    }
    return ""
}
function parse_msg(line) {
    if (match(line, /^[0-9]{4}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{2} [0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2} [A-Z]+: (.*)/)) {
        return substr(line, RSTART+RLENGTH, length(line))
    } else if (match(line, /"msg":"[^"]+"/)) {
        gsub(/"msg":"/, "", line)
        gsub(/".*/, "", line)
        return line
    }
    return ""
}
{
    ts = parse_ts($0)
    lvl = parse_level($0)
    msg = parse_msg($0)

    if (lvl == "ERROR" && ts != "") {
        key = FILENAME
        gsub(/\/logs\//, "", key)
        gsub(/\/events\.log.*/, "", key)

        if (!(key in error_counts)) {
            error_counts[key] = 0
        }
        error_counts[key]++

        if (!(msg in error_messages[key])) {
            error_messages[key][msg] = 0
        }
        error_messages[key][msg]++
    }
}
END {
    for (key in error_counts) {
        print "Tenant/Service: " key
        print "Total Errors: " error_counts[key]
        print "Top 3 Messages:"
        n = 0
        for (msg in error_messages[key]) {
            if (n++ >= 3) break
            print "  " error_messages[key][msg] "x: " msg
        }
        print ""
    }
}'
```

## Why This Is Asked
- Assesses ability to build robust, single-line data pipelines over multi-file logs, including compressed files, without external dependencies. 
- Tests time-window handling, cross-service aggregation, and per-tenant bucketing under rotation. 

## Key Concepts
- Stream processing with standard UNIX tools (find, xargs, zcat, awk). 
- JSON field extraction via regex in awk; resilient to line variations. 
- Time-window filtering using START/END derived from date; cross-file aggregation. 
- Sorting by computed metric (error rate) without extra tools.

## Code Example
```javascript
START=$(date -u -d "-6 hours" +"%Y-%m-%dT%H")
END=$(date -u +"%Y-%m-%dT%H")
find /var/log/cluster -type f \( -name '*.log' -o -name '*.log.gz' \) -print0 | \
  xargs -0 -I{} sh -lc 'case "{}" in *.gz) zcat "{}" ;; *) cat "{}" ;; esac' | \
  awk -v s="$START" -v e="$END" '{
    if (match($0, /"ts":"([^"]+)"/, a)) ts=a[1]; hour=substr(ts,1,13); gsub(/T/," ",hour); hour_key=hour;
    if (match($0, /"tenant":"([^"]+)"/, b)) tenant=b[1];
    if (match($0, /"lvl":"([^"]+)"/, c)) lvl=c[1];
    if (hour_key && tenant && hour_key>=s && hour_key<=e) {
      total[tenant] += 1; if (lvl=="ERROR") errors[tenant] += 1;
    }
  }
  END { for (t in total) { rate = total[t] ? errors[t] / total[t] : 0; printf "%s\t%.6f\n", t, rate } }
``` 

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adapt this to include per-hour breakdowns in addition to the overall top 3? 
- How would you handle non-UTC timestamps or malformed JSON lines?

## Why This Is Asked
This question tests the ability to handle mixed log formats with rotation, per-host aggregation, and time-windowed analysis using standard UNIX tools.

## Key Concepts
- Mixed log formats (standard access logs and JSON lines)
- Handling both .log and .log.gz files
- Graceful handling of unreadable files
- Time parsing and windowing in shell (epoch conversion)
- AWK associative arrays for per-host tallies
- Robust parsing of multi-line error blocks without double-counting

## Code Example
```bash
find /logs/nginx -type f -name '*.log*' -print0 | while IFS= read -r -d '' f; do
  if [[ "$f" == *.gz ]]; then
    zcat "$f" 2>/dev/null || continue
  else
    cat "$f" 2>/dev/null || continue
  fi
done | awk -v cutoff="$(date -d '2 hours ago' +%s)" '
/^ERROR:/ { error_block=1; next }
error_block && /^[[:space:]]/ { next }
error_block { error_block=0 }
{
  if (match($0, /\{"ts": *([0-9]+)/, ts)) {
    timestamp = ts[1]
  } else if (match($0, /^([0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3})/, host)) {
    split($0, parts, /\[/)
    if (match(parts[2], /([0-9]{2}\/[A-Za-z]{3}\/[0-9]{4}:[0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2})/, date_match)) {
      cmd = "date -d '\''" date_match[1] "\'' +%s"
      cmd | getline timestamp
      close(cmd)
    }
  }

  if (timestamp && timestamp >= cutoff) {
    if (match($0, /"status": *([45][0-9]{2})/, status)) {
      counts[host[1]]++
    } else if (match($0, /\s([45][0-9]{2})\s/, status)) {
      counts[host[1]]++
    }
  }
}
END {
  for (h in counts) print h ":" counts[h]
}' | sort
```

## Why This Is Asked
This question tests the ability to parse mixed log formats, handle multi-line events, and perform cross-file aggregation under log rotation. It assesses proficiency with standard UNIX pipeline tools and robust error handling.

## Key Concepts
- Parsing mixed plain-text and JSON log formats
- Time-window filtering with dynamic cutoff calculation
- Handling multi-line trace blocks and TRACE context markers
- Streaming large log sets efficiently with find and while loops
- Gracefully skipping unreadable files via 2>/dev/null redirects

## Code Example
```bash
# Stream all .log and .log.gz files, skip unreadable
find /logs/trace/ -type f \( -name '*.log' -o -name '*.log.gz' \) 2>/dev/null | \
while read -r f; do 
  case "$f" in 
    *.gz) zcat "$f" 2>/dev/null;; 
    *) cat "$f" 2>/dev/null;; 
  esac
done | awk -v cutoff=$(date -d '2 hours ago' '+%Y-%m-%d %H:%M') '
  # Parse JSON lines with ERROR level, extract trace_id
  /^\{/ { 
    if ($0 ~ /"lvl":.*"ERROR"/) { 
      match($0, /"trace_id":"([^"]+)"/, t); 
      if (t[1] && $0 >= cutoff) errcnt[t[1]]++ 
    } 
  }
  # Parse plain-text lines with ERROR level
  /^\d{4}-/ { 
    if ($0 ~ /ERROR/) { 
      match($0, /\[([^\]]+)\]/, t); 
      if (t[1]) errcnt[t[1]]++ 
    } 
  }
  END { for (id in errcnt) print id ": " errcnt[id] }
'
```

